The paper discusses a new approach to learning generative autoencoding models using optimal transport and the p-Wasserstein distance. This is a topic that falls under the broad category of machine learning, specifically in the subfields of deep learning and generative models. Therefore, the most likely category is cs.LG (Machine Learning). Additionally, the paper discusses the use of neural networks and backpropagation, which are common techniques in artificial intelligence (cs.AI). The paper also includes experiments on benchmark datasets, which suggests a focus on computer vision (cs.CV). The use of the Sinkhorn algorithm, which is a tool from information theory, suggests a possible connection to the subfield of neural information processing (cs.NE). Finally, the paper discusses the use of different metric spaces and priors, which could be related to the subfield of information theory (cs.IT).
